pr_review_body:
@Wck-iipi  I learned in a follow-up discussion with @bjester that the logic used here is duplicitous of code already available between `useDevices` and the `SelectDeviceModalGroup/api.js`.

This logic I believe should instead implement a filtering function which checks if a device has a facility with sign-ups allowed. This would be akin to the [`facilityIsAvailableAtDevice`](https://github.com/learningequality/kolibri/blob/545ceaedb682e694f830233fd3ed7ba442391df0/kolibri/core/assets/src/views/sync/SelectDeviceModalGroup/api.js#L31-L35) function.

However, the new function would just take the `deviceId` and return if any of the facilities have the ability to allow sign ups like this (I've not tested this):

```
export function deviceFacilityCanSignUp(deviceId) {
    return NetworkLocationResource.fetchFacilities(deviceId)
        .then(({ facilities }) => {
             return facilities.some(f => f.learner_can_sign_up));
        });
}
```

In this case then, we can get the list of devices using `useDevicesForLearnOnlyDevice` from `useDevices` to get a pre-filtered list of devices which is necessary for this particular case. Then iterate over these devices, calling the new function above for each device, and you can then know which devices should be shown in this case.

In this case now the `SelectDeviceForm` doesn't have to worry about maintaining a list of facilities, but rather can just hone in on which devices are useful in a particular case.

---

The change requests here are substantial -- essentially reworking most of what you've added. This issue is also a relatively urgent fix in our pipeline, which I want to share because we don't expect that your contributions will necessarily align with our plans.

If you'd like to take another shot this week, please let me know along with any questions and I'll do my best to clarify. If not, then I totally understand and greatly appreciate the work you've put in on this. It opened up a greater discussion around keeping our code extensible which is invaluable in any case.

@mgberg the PR looks pretty good, I made some minor changes to get validation to pass and to add some additional type hints:

- https://github.com/corning-incorporated/rdflib/pull/1

If you make PRs, it is better to make it from your personal account, that way we can push to your branch instead of needing to make PR to your branch.

Wait, what is the actual root cause for logs not being persisted? After #30849 the length should always be short enough?

The `raise e` change won't do much as we catch everything in the outer loop in `glue.py`:

```
    for reporter in reporters:
        try:
            reporter.report_result(test, result)
        except Exception as e:
            logger.error(f"Error reporting results via {type(reporter)}: {e}")
```

I'm open to raising an error, but if we do, let's please raise an exception that inherits `ReleaseTestError` and is associated to a proper exit code. IMO it should be a new exit code in the "hard infra error (non-retryable)" section

Thank you for this @KushalBeniwal ! 

That failing check is definitely not related - a bunch of the latest PRs are failing so we'll work that out - but this PR is good to go!

@jonboiser we merge this to 0.14.x instead of develop since we'll merge it forward soon enough?

@sawradip There is nothing more you need to do, after pushing to your branch, the PR is updated automatically.

Thanks for implementing the remaining fixes. the `Transfer_Learning.ipynb` notebook looks much better now.

I'm ready to merge, but will leave this PR open for a few days in case @ottonemo or @thomasjpfan want to add anything.

Thank you for your proposal @carylee.

The annotations we'll need here are a little bit more subtle, as we have to capture dependency between inputs and outputs. It should be something around these lines:

```python
    @overload
    def approxQuantile(
        self,
        col: str,
        probabilities: Union[List[float], Tuple[float]],
        relativeError: float
    ) -> List[float]: ...
    @overload
    def approxQuantile(
        self,
        col: Union[List[str], Tuple[str]],
        probabilities: Union[List[float], Tuple[float]],
        relativeError: float
    ) -> List[List[float]]: ...
```

So if the input is a string, the output is a list of strings. Otherwise a list of lists of strings.

Thank you! I have just one suggestion.

It looks like you've already signed https://github.com/Pylons/waitress/blob/master/CONTRIBUTORS.txt#L130, so we're good there.

@mmerickel or @bertjwregeer have final review as maintainers.
